{
  "answer": "**Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana** (by Unknown), *Chapter 1*.[^1]\n\nIn this Kawi Buddhist allegorical tale, the Buddha (appearing as Vairocana/Śākyamuni) instructs the pupil Kuñjarakarṇa (a rākṣasa ascetic) on the origins of the body while teaching *dharma* in his monastery.[^2] The key verse occurs in Canto 17, verse 8:\n\n> From the *liṅga* of your father you emerged, like molten tin, poured out.  \n> Indeed, Kāma is its name; Ratih is your name when you clung to your mother.[^3]\n\nThis imagery follows immediately after, with the embryo forming \"in the blossoming lotus of your mother's womb,\"[^4] and pairs with a scheme of **five souls** (*ātmā*, *parātmā*, *antarātmā*, *nirātmā*, *cetanātmā*) joined to the **five great elements** (earth/*cetanātmā*; water/*nirātmā*; fire/*ātmā*; wind/*antarātmā*; ether/*parātmā*), as the body coalesces.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Full chapter: [/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/].\n[^2]: Context in Cantos 17–20: read_chapter result, e.g., [p-fd135e], [p-1082d7], [p-4edd93].\n[^3]: [/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-1082d7].\n[^4]: Same paragraph.\n[^5]: [/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-4edd93], [#p-2af4c4], [#p-b206c8], [#p-8e6c10].",
